  <main>
    <!-- Unit 1 -->
    <section class="unit u1" id="unit1">
      <div class="title">
        <div>
          <h2>Unit 1 — Cloud Computing Basics</h2>
          <div class="meta">Advantages, disadvantages, characteristics, service and deployment models</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-list">
        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q1</div>
            <div class="qtext">Advantages & Disadvantages of Cloud Computing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <strong>Advantages</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Cost efficiency — less hardware and maintenance.</li>
              <li>Scalability — grow or shrink resources on demand.</li>
              <li>Accessibility — access anywhere via Internet.</li>
              <li>Automatic updates — provider manages updates and security.</li>
              <li>Disaster recovery — simpler and cheaper backups.</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Disadvantages</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Internet dependency — needs stable connection.</li>
              <li>Security concerns — data stored offsite.</li>
              <li>Limited control — vendor manages many aspects.</li>
              <li>Downtime risk — outages can affect access.</li>
              <li>Hidden costs — extra charges for storage or transfers.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q2</div>
            <div class="qtext">Characteristics of Cloud Computing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ul>
              <li>On-demand self-service — start services when needed.</li>
              <li>Broad network access — reachable from many devices.</li>
              <li>Resource pooling — shared resources among users.</li>
              <li>Rapid elasticity — scale resources quickly.</li>
              <li>Measured service — usage is monitored and billed.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q3</div>
            <div class="qtext">Cloud Service Models — SaaS, PaaS, IaaS</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ul>
              <li><strong>SaaS</strong>: Ready-to-use applications (e.g., Google Workspace).</li>
              <li><strong>PaaS</strong>: Platforms for developing and deploying apps (e.g., App Engine).</li>
              <li><strong>IaaS</strong>: Virtual infrastructure like VMs (e.g., EC2).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q4</div>
            <div class="qtext">Deployment Models — Public, Private, Hybrid, Community</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Public</strong>: Shared by provider, low cost (AWS, Azure).</li>
              <li><strong>Private</strong>: Single organization, higher security.</li>
              <li><strong>Hybrid</strong>: Mix of public + private; flexible.</li>
              <li><strong>Community</strong>: Shared by similar organizations (colleges, hospitals).</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Unit 2 -->
    <section class="unit u2" id="unit2">
      <div class="title">
        <div>
          <h2>Unit 2 — Virtualization Concepts</h2>
          <div class="meta">OS-level virtualization, network virtualization, app virtualization, cloud vs virtualization</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-list">
        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q1</div>
            <div class="qtext">OS-level Virtualization & its use</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p>Containers run multiple isolated user spaces on one OS kernel. They behave like lightweight virtual machines and help improve resource use, enable fast deployment, and scale efficiently.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q2</div>
            <div class="qtext">Virtualization: Network virtualization benefits & limitations</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Creating virtual versions of physical resources (servers, storage, networks).</p>
            <strong>Benefits</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Better resource utilization.</li>
              <li>Simplified management.</li>
              <li>Isolation improves security.</li>
              <li>Scalable and cost efficient.</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Limitations</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Setup complexity.</li>
              <li>Some performance overhead.</li>
              <li>Security risks if misconfigured.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q3</div>
            <div class="qtext">Application Virtualization</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p>Apps run in isolated environments without direct installation on the host OS. Reduces compatibility issues and eases deployment. Examples: Microsoft App-V, VMware ThinApp.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q4</div>
            <div class="qtext">Virtualization vs Cloud Computing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p><strong>Virtualization</strong> is the technology that creates virtual resources. <strong>Cloud computing</strong> is a service model that uses virtualization to deliver scalable, on-demand services over the Internet. Key difference: virtualization is a technology; cloud is a model built on that technology.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Unit 3 -->
    <section class="unit u3" id="unit3">
      <div class="title">
        <div>
          <h2>Unit 3 — Cloud Risks and Storage</h2>
          <div class="meta">Risks, risk management steps, DAS / SAN / NAS, CIA triad</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-list">
        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q1</div>
            <div class="qtext">Types of Risks in Cloud</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ul>
              <li>Security risks — data breaches.</li>
              <li>Compliance risks — legal and regulatory failure.</li>
              <li>Operational risks — outages and downtime.</li>
              <li>Data loss — deletion or corruption.</li>
              <li>Vendor lock-in — hard to move providers.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q2</div>
            <div class="qtext">Six steps of Risk Management</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ol>
              <li>Identify risks</li>
              <li>Analyze risks</li>
              <li>Evaluate risks</li>
              <li>Treat or mitigate risks</li>
              <li>Monitor risks</li>
              <li>Review and improve</li>
            </ol>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q3</div>
            <div class="qtext">DAS, SAN, NAS — quick definitions</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ul>
              <li><strong>DAS</strong>: Direct Attached Storage — storage directly on a server (local drives).</li>
              <li><strong>SAN</strong>: Storage Area Network — high-speed block-level storage network for servers.</li>
              <li><strong>NAS</strong>: Network Attached Storage — file-level shared storage accessible over a network.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q4</div>
            <div class="qtext">Data Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability (CIA)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Confidentiality</strong>: Protect data from unauthorized access.</li>
              <li><strong>Integrity</strong>: Ensure data is accurate and unaltered.</li>
              <li><strong>Availability</strong>: Ensure authorized users can access data when needed.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Unit 4 -->
    <section class="unit u4" id="unit4">
      <div class="title">
        <div>
          <h2>Unit 4 — Cloud Service Providers</h2>
          <div class="meta">Azure, Google Cloud, AWS, HPC in cloud</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-list">
        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q1</div>
            <div class="qtext">Microsoft Azure — definition, components, benefits</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p><strong>Definition:</strong> Azure is a cloud platform offering IaaS, PaaS, SaaS.</p>
            <strong>Components:</strong> Compute (VMs, containers), Storage (blob, disk), Networking (VNets, load balancers), Databases (SQL, managed DBs).</p>
            <strong>Benefits:</strong> Scalability, security, integration with Microsoft tools, flexible pricing.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q2</div>
            <div class="qtext">Google Cloud — apps and App Engine</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p>Google Apps include Gmail, Docs, Drive, Meet. <strong>App Engine</strong> is a PaaS for building and deploying apps with automatic scaling and easy integration with other Google services.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q3</div>
            <div class="qtext">AWS — EC2, S3, DynamoDB</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <ul>
              <li><strong>EC2</strong>: Virtual servers for compute.</li>
              <li><strong>S3</strong>: Object storage for backups, hosting.</li>
              <li><strong>DynamoDB</strong>: Managed NoSQL database for high performance.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q4</div>
            <div class="qtext">HPC and Cloud</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p>HPC uses powerful compute to solve complex problems. Cloud offers on-demand powerful resources, scalable clusters, cost savings versus owning a supercomputer, and easier collaboration.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Unit 5 -->
    <section class="unit u5" id="unit5">
      <div class="title">
        <div>
          <h2>Unit 5 — Jungle Computing</h2>
          <div class="meta">Combining heterogeneous compute for big workloads</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="qa-list">
        <div class="qa" onclick="toggle(this)">
          <div class="q">
            <div class="chip">Q1</div>
            <div class="qtext">What is Jungle Computing?</div>
          </div>
          <div class="a">
            <p>Jungle Computing links different computing environments (clouds, clusters, grids, supercomputers) into one system so applications use the best available resources together.</p>
            <strong>Features:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Heterogeneity — many types of systems.</li>
              <li>Scalability and fault tolerance.</li>
              <li>Resource sharing and dynamic allocation.</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Applications:</strong> Scientific research, machine learning, big data analytics. Example: a lab using a supercomputer, cloud bursts, and local servers for simulations.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>

